323
36:24.960 --> 36:32.700
of the four Bell states she
would like to share with Bob, and she has the freedom to choose by acting on her qubit alone

324
36:32.700 --> 36:36.840
and that's a pretty interesting
aspect of entanglement.

325
36:36.840 --> 36:44.640
Alice then sends her qubit
to Bob, at this point, Bob holds one of the four Bell states and he just needs to
figure out which one it is

326
36:44.640 --> 36:47.910
to recover the bits.

327
36:47.910 --> 36:55.950
And we can check that
indeed a controlled NOT gate followed by a Hadamard gate
as we have in the diagram does the right thing.

328
36:55.950 --> 37:03.780
I won't go through them in detail, but if you choose to do that, you'll find that the effect is
as you see here in the table.

329
37:03.780 --> 37:11.340
One way to check that
is simply to compute. Alternatively, we can recognize that we actually already
went through this in reverse

330
37:11.340 --> 37:18.300
in the previous lesson. In the previous lesson we
had the Hadamard gate first and the controlled NOT gate second

331
37:18.300 --> 37:26.430
and we saw that that circuit
mapped standard basis states to Bell states with a pesky
minus sign in one of the cases.

332
37:26.430 --> 37:35.490
When we reverse the order of the gates and we consider the fact
that both of these two gates are their own inverses,
what we get is the inverse,

333
37:35.490 --> 37:42.720
and so what we have in this
case is the action goes in the opposite direction
and the minus sign can choose whichever
side it wants to be on,

334
37:42.720 --> 37:49.980
but otherwise, it's where it belongs, and at this point it's
immediate that the measurement reveals the correct values,

335
37:49.980 --> 37:57.930
the minus sign here doesn't bother us because one appears with
probability one in this case, and that's all there is to the analysis.

336
37:57.930 --> 38:04.500
In a nutshell, Alice picks a Bell state and Bob figures out which one it is.

337
38:04.500 --> 38:12.150
Just a couple of brief remarks
about superdense coding before we move on; first, we should acknowledge
that superdense coding

338
38:12.150 --> 38:20.130
is probably not likely
to be useful or practical in any sense as a means to
transmit classical information.

339
38:20.130 --> 38:26.850
Classical communication
is very inexpensive and physically sending Qubits is challenging to say the least,

340
38:26.850 --> 38:34.800
and so long as that's the case, we wouldn't expect any
practical advantage at all to come from superdense coding.

341
38:34.800 --> 38:39.780
But just because it isn't
likely to be practical doesn't mean that superdense
coding is not interesting.

342
38:39.780 --> 38:46.650
It's very interesting in fact, for one, the underlying idea is
really quite fundamental,

343
38:46.650 --> 38:52.710
and when I refer to the underlying idea, I mean the idea that if Alice
shares a Bell state with Bob,

344
38:52.710 --> 39:02.100
then she can choose to change that state to any other Bell state that
she chooses all by herself, she doesn't need Bob's
help at all to do that.

345
39:02.100 --> 39:09.060
This is a specific example
that concerns the Bell states, but there's a more general underlying idea that concerns the freedom that one player

346
39:09.060 --> 39:16.110
has to transform an entangled state that's shared with another player, and understanding exactly
what that freedom is

347
39:16.110 --> 39:23.010
is an important step in understanding quantum information and we'll see exactly how to describe that freedom in simple

348
39:23.010 --> 39:27.180
and elegant terms In the
third unit of the series.

349
39:27.180 --> 39:34.500
Superdense coding also
provides a concrete example of what you can do with entanglement, which is to allow two classical
bits to be transmitted

350
39:34.500 --> 39:45.636
by sending a single qubit. As I already mentioned, this
is provably not possible by Holevo's theorem without entanglement.

351
39:45.636 --> 39:52.620
We can also consider teleportation and superdense coding together, and we see that they
establish an equivalence

352
39:52.620 --> 39:58.890
between one qubit of quantum communication and two bits of classical communication.

353
39:58.890 --> 40:04.530
As long as you're willing
to spend one e-bit, you can effectively
convert one to the other.

354
40:04.530 --> 40:11.970
Teleportation allows for the
communication of one qubit using two classical bits of communication and superdense coding goes the other way

355
40:11.970 --> 40:18.150
and allows two classical
bits of communication using one qubit of quantum communication.

356
40:18.150 --> 40:26.640
Without spending the e-bit, however, you cannot transform
either one into the other, it's entanglement that
makes this possible.

357
40:26.640 --> 40:35.190
The third and final example
that we'll cover in this lesson is not a protocol but a
game known as the CHSH game.

358
40:35.190 --> 40:41.220
When we talk about a game in this context, we're not talking about something that's meant to be
played for fun or sport,

359
40:41.220 --> 40:47.460
but rather a mathematical abstraction in the sense of game theory for instance.

360
40:47.460 --> 40:55.470
Mathematical abstractions of games are very commonly studied in
economics and computer science, for instance, and there's
quite a lot of value

361
40:55.470 --> 41:01.470
to be found in the abstraction, so games are not all fun
in games as it turns out,

362
41:01.470 --> 41:04.961
although it is fun to think about them.

363
41:04.961 --> 41:13.770
In this particular case, what we have is essentially
a thought experiment that can be described in a
pretty intuitive way as a game.

364
41:13.770 --> 41:23.370
The letters CHSH refer to the authors, John Clauser, Michael
Horne, Abner Shimony, and Richard Holt of a 1969
paper where the example

365
41:23.370 --> 41:30.330
was first described. They didn't describe
it as a game, in fact, and it's pretty common
to refer to this example

366
41:30.330 --> 41:36.060
not as the CHSH game, but
rather as the CHSH inequality.

367
41:36.060 --> 41:41.730
For a computer scientist like me, however, it's just very natural
to describe it as a game.

368
41:41.730 --> 41:48.840
I've already suggested that
mathematical abstractions of games are both important and useful and there are many different
categories of games

